This is a very good question, and it gets to the heart of how to use HPC resources correctly with future / doFuture—without falling into the trap of nested parallelism.
I’ll structure the answer as follows:
Key principle: why nested parallelism is usually the wrong abstraction
How future actually maps work to CPUs / cores
How to fully exploit multi‑CPU, multi‑core machines with one loop
What to do instead of plan(list("multisession", "sequential"))
Concrete patterns you can use in simulation studies
All recommendations are consistent with the future and doFuture design philosophy. [dofuture.f...everse.org], [henrikbeng....github.io], [cran.r-project.org]
1. Key principle: don’t use nested parallelism for hardware utilization
The important conceptual shift is this:
Parallelism should describe tasks, not hardware topology.
Using two nested loops because “the cluster has CPUs and each CPU has cores” is not how future wants you to think.
Reasons nested parallelism is discouraged:
Oversubscription (too many R processes competing for the same cores)
Poor load balancing
Complicated RNG reasoning
Unpredictable performance
This is exactly why future defaults to one parallel layer only and why nested plans like
plan(list("multisession", "sequential"))
exist mainly as an escape hatch, not a best practice.
2. How future actually maps to HPC hardware
What multisession does
plan(multisession)
Starts one R worker per available core (by default)
Each worker is a separate R process
OS + scheduler decide which CPU socket runs which worker
NUMA / CPU topology is handled by the OS, not by R
So on:
2 CPUs × 32 cores → you effectively get 64 workers
No need to model CPUs explicitly in your code
This behavior is intentional and documented in the future framework. [henrikbeng....github.io]
3. How to fully exploit multi‑CPU, multi‑core machines with ONE loop
The correct abstraction: many independent tasks
If you have 100 000 simulations, treat them as 100 000 independent tasks:
 
library(doFuture)
plan(multisession)
 
y <- foreach(k = 1:1e5,
             .options.future = list(seed = TRUE)) %dofuture% {
  rnorm(1)
}
 
What happens:
Tasks are chunked automatically
Workers pull tasks dynamically
All cores across all CPUs are used
No nested parallelism needed
This is exactly how future achieves scalability on HPC systems. [dofuture.f...everse.org], [cran.r-project.org]
4. “But I want to control granularity” → use chunking, not nesting
If each iteration is too cheap, you can increase task granularity without nesting.
Option A: scheduling ratio
 
foreach(k = 1:1e5,
        .options.future = list(seed = TRUE,
                               scheduling = 2)) %dofuture% {
  rnorm(1)
}
 
Each worker gets ≈2 chunks
Fewer task handovers
Better for cheap computations
Option B: explicit chunk size
 
foreach(k = 1:1e5,
        .options.future = list(seed = TRUE,
                               chunk.size = 500)) %dofuture% {
  rnorm(1)
}
 
This is the recommended replacement for nested loops in simulation work. [cran.r-project.org]
5. If you really have two conceptual levels (outer × inner)
Sometimes you logically have two levels (e.g. scenarios × replicates).
Still: parallelize only one level.
Pattern A (recommended): parallel outer, sequential inner
 
y <- foreach(scenario = 1:100,
             .options.future = list(seed = TRUE)) %dofuture% {
  replicate(1000, rnorm(1))
}
 
Advantages:
Clear semantics
One RNG stream per scenario
No nested futures
Excellent reproducibility
Pattern B: flatten the design
 
design <- expand.grid(
  scenario = 1:100,
  rep       = 1:1000
)
 
y <- foreach(i = seq_len(nrow(design)),
             .options.future = list(seed = TRUE)) %dofuture% {
  rnorm(1)
}
 
This is often ideal for large simulation studies (e.g. operating characteristics).
6. When is nested parallelism justified?
Very rarely. Typical valid cases:
Inner loop calls non‑R parallel code (e.g. OpenMP in C++)
Explicit MPI workflows
GPU + CPU hybrid setups
For standard R simulation work (including oncology trial simulations):
Nested %dofuture% is almost always an antipattern.
7. Practical BI / HPC recommendation (summary)
Do this:
✅ One multisession plan
✅ One parallel loop
✅ Use scheduling / chunk.size
✅ Let the OS + scheduler map workers to CPUs
✅ Use seed = TRUE
Avoid this:
❌ Nested %dofuture%
❌ Nested plans for CPU topology
❌ Manually mapping CPUs in R
❌ set.seed() inside loops
